  "editorial": {
    "headline": "NYY 6, BOS 1.",
    "subheadline": "New York Yankees beats Boston Red Sox.",
    "lead_angle": "Jazz Chisholm Jr. crushed a three-run home run to right field in the eighth, shattering a deadlock and launching the New York Yankees to a 6-1 victory over the Boston Red Sox at Yankee Stadium. The late-game explosion silenced the visiting nine, giving winning pitcher Tim Hill the decision after he tossed a scoreless top of the eighth. Justin Slaten, on for the Red Sox, took the loss after surrendering four runs in the pivotal frame.\n\nThe contest remained a tight struggle through seven innings, a classic division matchup. New York had scratched across the first run in the fifth when Paul Goldschmidt singled home Trent Grisham. Boston answered quickly, tying the score in the sixth on a groundout from Jarren Duran. It stayed knotted 1-1 until the bottom of the eighth, when the Yankees bats erupted. Trent Grisham opened the frame with a single, followed by a Paul Goldschmidt base hit. After an out, Cody Bellinger singled to load the bases before Jazz Chisholm Jr.'s blast cleared them, swinging the game firmly in the Yankees' favor.\n\nChisholm Jr.'s 1-for-4 night included the game-altering home run and three runs batted in, making him the difference-maker in a crucial divisional tilt. Trent Grisham also shined, collecting three hits and an RBI. This win pushes the New York Yankees further ahead in the AL East standings, extending their lead over their bitter rivals and intensifying the pressure on Boston as the season progresses.",
    "reason": "Best game on today's slate."
